result.execSummary:
The defendant Cincere Jaylon Wells was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possess Firearm-Adjudicated Deliquent of a Felony, a class G felony, Wisconsin Statutes 941.29(1m)(bm).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt:
Defendant Cincere Jaylon Wells in court with attorney Tedia K. Gamino.  Ian F Vance-Curzan appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Parties have reached a resolution. State places offer on the record. 

Defense and defendant are in agreement.  

Defendant changes plea to GUILTY as to COUNT 3.  

Pursuant to negotiations and on the Motion of the State, Court Ordered COUNT 1 AND 2 DISMISSED BUT READ IN for the purpose of sentencing.

Defendant examined as to plea, advised of Constitutional rights and the maximum penalty.  Defendant further advised that if not a US citizen deportation is possible. Court found that defendant freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived their rights.  Plea questionnaire, addendum and jury instructions received and filed.  Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea. Court found defendant guilty as charged in the information and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record.  

Defendant is advised is a convicted felon and may not possess any firearms.  
Defendant is advised unable to vote in any election until civil rights are restored.  

Filed:
Amended Plea Questionnaire and Waiver of Rights and Addendum

Sentencing proceeded. Statements by parties and defendant. Defendant's Mother Lakisha W. makes statement. 

The court sentenced the defendant to a MAXIMUM term in the Wisconsin State Prison of 5 YEARS AND 6 MONTHS, credit for 93 DAYS time served. The term of INITIAL CONFINEMENT is 2 YEARS AND 6 MONTHS, the term of EXTENDED SUPERVISION is 3 YEARS. Court STAYED the sentence and placed the defendant on probation for 3 YEARS.

CONDITIONS OF PROBATION/EXTENDED SUPERVISION:
- Serve 60 days condition time in the House of Correction; STAYED to be used at the discretion of the probation agent.
- Provide a DNA sample. 
- AODA assessment; comply with any treatment.
- Maintain full-time work or school or combination of both. 
- Complete high school courses and obtain diploma.
- NO CONTACT with Cobe N.
- NO CONTACT with any associates of THE RENZO BOYS

- Pay all MANDATORY court costs, fees, and surcharges including: DNA surcharges to be paid during period of probation, if revoked to be paid by defendant's prison funds at a percentage to be determined by the DOC, remainder to be paid during the period of extended supervision; failure to pay will result in a civil judgment.

*Court finds defendant is eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program after serving 1 year.
*Court finds defendant is NOT eligible for the Wisconsin Substance Abuse Program.
*Court advised defendant of right to seek post conviction relief.
*Court advised due to felony conviction the defendant is prohibited from firearm possession, and defendant's voting rights are suspended and may not vote until civil rights are restored.
*Court denies Defense's request for expungement.
